				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Val=
ue approached by a mathematical object</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">For other us=
es, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_(disambiguation)#Mat=
hematics" class=3D"mw-redirect mw-disambig" title=3D"Limit (disambiguation)=
">Limit =C2=A7 Mathematics</a>.</div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathem=
atics">mathematics</a>, a <b>limit</b> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Value_(mathematics)" title=3D"Value (mathematics)">value</a> th=
at a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Function_(mathematics)" title=
=3D"Function (mathematics)">function</a> (or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Sequence" title=3D"Sequence">sequence</a>) approaches as the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Argument_of_a_function" title=3D"Argu=
ment of a function">argument</a> (or index) approaches some value.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Limit_(mathematics)#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Limit_of_a_function" title=3D"Limit of a function">Limits of fu=
nctions</a> are essential to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calcu=
lus" title=3D"Calculus">calculus</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Mathematical_analysis" title=3D"Mathematical analysis">mathematical =
analysis</a>, and are used to define <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Continuous_function" title=3D"Continuous function">continuity</a>, <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derivative" title=3D"Derivative">deriva=
tives</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral" title=3D"=
Integral">integrals</a>.
The concept of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_of_a_sequen=
ce" title=3D"Limit of a sequence">limit of a sequence</a> is further genera=
lized to the concept of a limit of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Net_(topology)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Net (topology)">topologic=
al net</a>, and is closely related to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Limit_(category_theory)" title=3D"Limit (category theory)">limit</a> an=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Direct_limit" title=3D"Direct li=
mit">direct limit</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Category_=
theory" title=3D"Category theory">category theory</a>.
The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_inferior_and_limit_super=
ior" title=3D"Limit inferior and limit superior">limit inferior and limit s=
uperior</a> provide generalizations of the concept of a limit which are par=
ticularly relevant when the limit at a point may not exist.
</p>
