<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLimit_(mathematics)&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>According to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermann_Hankel" ti=
tle=3D"Hermann Hankel">Hankel</a> (1871), the modern concept of limit origi=
nates from Proposition X.1 of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eucl=
id%27s_Elements" title=3D"Euclid's Elements">Euclid's Elements</a>, which f=
orms the basis of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Method_of_ex=
haustion" title=3D"Method of exhaustion">Method of exhaustion</a> found in =
Euclid and Archimedes: "Two unequal magnitudes being set out, if from the g=
reater there is subtracted a magnitude greater than its half, and from that=
 which is left a magnitude greater than its half, and if this process is re=
peated continually, then there will be left some magnitude less than the le=
sser magnitude set out."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_(mathematics)#cite_note-2"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p><sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Limit_(mathematics)#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gr%C3%A9goire_de_Saint-Vinc=
ent" title=3D"Gr=C3=A9goire de Saint-Vincent">Gr=C3=A9goire de Saint-Vincen=
t</a> gave the first definition of limit (terminus) of a <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometric_series" title=3D"Geometric series">geometr=
ic series</a> in his work <i>Opus Geometricum</i> (1647): "The <i>terminus<=
/i> of a progression is the end of the series, which none progression can r=
each, even not if she is continued in infinity, but which she can approach =
nearer than a given segment."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_(mathematics)#cite_note-4"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup>
</p><p>In the Scholium to <span title=3D"Latin-language text"><i lang=3D"la=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosophi%C3%A6_Naturalis_Princ=
ipia_Mathematica" title=3D"Philosophi=C3=A6 Naturalis Principia Mathematica=
">Principia</a></i></span> in 1687, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Isaac_Newton" title=3D"Isaac Newton">Isaac Newton</a> had a clear definit=
ion of a limit, stating that "Those ultimate ratios&nbsp;... are not actual=
ly ratios of ultimate quantities, but limits&nbsp;... which they can approa=
ch so closely that their difference is less than any given quantity".<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-:17_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Limit_(mathematics)#cite_note-:17-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The modern definition of a limit goes back to <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernard_Bolzano" title=3D"Bernard Bolzano">Bernard Bolza=
no</a> who, in 1817, developed the basics of the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Epsilon-delta" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Epsilon-delta"=
>epsilon-delta</a> technique to define continuous functions. However, his w=
ork remained unknown to other mathematicians until thirty years after his d=
eath.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Limit_(mathematics)#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Augustin-Louis_Cauchy" titl=
e=3D"Augustin-Louis Cauchy">Augustin-Louis Cauchy</a> in 1821,<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-Larson_7-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Limit_(mathematics)#cite_note-Larson-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> followed by <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Weierstrass" title=3D"Karl Weierstra=
ss">Karl Weierstrass</a>, formalized the definition of the limit of a funct=
ion which became known as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/(%CE=
%B5,_%CE%B4)-definition_of_limit" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"(=CE=B5, =
=CE=B4)-definition of limit">(=CE=B5, =CE=B4)-definition of limit</a>.
</p><p>The modern notation of placing the arrow below the limit symbol was =
invented by John Gaston Leathem in 1905 and popularized by <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G._H._Hardy" title=3D"G. H. Hardy">G. H. Hardy</a>=
's 1908 textbook <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Course_of_Pu=
re_Mathematics" title=3D"A Course of Pure Mathematics">A Course of Pure Mat=
hematics</a></i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_(mathematics)#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Types_of_limits">Types of l=
imits</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLimit_=
(mathematics)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Typ=
es of limits"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"In_sequences">In sequences<=
/h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLimit_(mathe=
matics)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: In sequen=
ces"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></=
span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_of_a_sequence"=
 title=3D"Limit of a sequence">Limit of a sequence</a></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Real_numbers">Real numbers<=
/h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLimit_(mathe=
matics)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Real numb=
ers"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></=
span></div>
<p>The expression <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/0.999..." title=
=3D"0.999...">0.999...</a> should be interpreted as the limit of the sequen=
ce 0.9, 0.99, 0.999, ... and so on. This sequence can be rigorously shown t=
o have the limit 1, and therefore this expression is meaningfully interpret=
ed as having the value 1.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_(mathematics)#cite_note-9"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p>
</p><p>Formally, suppose <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sub>1</sub>, <i>a=
</i><sub>2</sub>, ...</span> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Sequence" title=3D"Sequence">sequence</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Real_number" title=3D"Real number">real numbers</a>. When the li=
mit of the sequence exists, the real number <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">L</span> is the <i>limit</i> of this sequence <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/If_and_only_if" title=3D"If and only=
 if">if and only if</a> for every <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Real_number" title=3D"Real number">real number</a> <span class=3D"texhtml">=
<i>=CE=B5</i> &gt; 0</span>, there exists a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Natural_number" title=3D"Natural number">natural number</a> <span=
 class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">N</span> such that for=
 all <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> &gt; <i>N</i></span>, we have <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml">|<span class=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-left:0.1em; paddi=
ng-right:0.1em;"><i>a</i><sub><i>n</i></sub> =E2=88=92 <i>L</i></span>| &lt=
; <i>=CE=B5</i></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_(mathematics)#cite_note-10"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
The common notation
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle \lim _{n\to \infty }a_{n}=3DL}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <munder>
          <mo movablelimits=3D"true" form=3D"prefix">lim</mo>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>n</mi>
            <mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=92<!-- =E2=86=92 --></mo>
            <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=E2=88=9E<!-- =E2=88=9E --></mi>
          </mrow>
        </munder>
        <msub>
          <mi>a</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>n</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>L</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \lim _{n\to \=
infty }a_{n}=3DL}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
