<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Computability">Computabilit=
y</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLimit_(mat=
hematics)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D29" title=3D"Edit section: Comput=
ability"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<p>Limits can be difficult to compute. There exist limit expressions whose =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modulus_of_convergence" title=3D"M=
odulus of convergence">modulus of convergence</a> is <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Undecidable_problem" title=3D"Undecidable problem">undec=
idable</a>. In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Recursion_theory" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Recursion theory">recursion theory</a>, the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_lemma" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Limit lemma">limit lemma</a> proves that it is possible to encode =
undecidable problems using limits.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_(mathematics)#cite_note-1=
5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p><p>There are several theorems or tests that indicate whether the limit =
exists. These are known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Converg=
ence_tests" title=3D"Convergence tests">convergence tests</a>. Examples inc=
lude the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ratio_test" title=3D"Rati=
o test">ratio test</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Squ=
eeze_theorem" title=3D"Squeeze theorem">squeeze theorem</a>. However they m=
ay not tell how to compute the limit.
</p>
